author: Klein, Naomi
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: 3.4/5 Okay- so this book is good and worth the read. However, I did find myself wishing that the arguments Klein presents in here were more even-hande3.4/5 Okay- so this book is good and worth the read. However, I did find myself wishing that the arguments Klein presents in here were more even-handed and grounded in reason. So much of her framing of “disaster capitalism” is hinged on anecdotes and emotional appeals- and what is most frustrating for me is that it didn’t need to be this way. Don’t get me wrong, some of the anecdotes and insights provided are spot-on…. but it sucks that these valid critiques of Friedmanism are mixed up with so many lies and half-truths that only serve to weaken the overall argument. Klein’s insights were cutting-edge at the time, but in retrospect feel shoddy and under-researched, and she bombards us with so many global problems while failing to prescribe any workable solutions....more

title: Between the Lines: Israel, the Palestinians, and the U.S. War on Terror
author: Honig-Parnass, Tikva
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: 3.4/5An illuminating collection of essays that filled-in many gaps in my knowledge of the Israeli-Palestinian conflict. This book specifically focuses3.4/5An illuminating collection of essays that filled-in many gaps in my knowledge of the Israeli-Palestinian conflict. This book specifically focuses on the time period between the beginning of the Second Intifada (2000-2005) up to the election of Hamas in Gaza (2006). It includes commentary on the U.S. role in legitimizing the “War on Terror” (in Iraq and elsewhere in the Middle East) and how it changed the political dynamics in Israel in regards to the Palestinians. It also speaks a lot to the moral bankruptcy and ultimate decline of the Zionist Left in Israel- and how it subsequently facilitated in disastrous and blatantly genocidal actions taken by the Israeli government since the turn of the century. I wouldn’t say that this is the most comprehensive account of the conflict to exist, but it posits some important ideas and presents an incisive political history that offers important context for current Israeli bombardement of Gaza....more

review: 4.2/5Hands down, one of the best celebrity memoirs I’ve ever read. Julia Fox is a fantastic writer- and despite being only 33 years old and only very 4.2/5Hands down, one of the best celebrity memoirs I’ve ever read. Julia Fox is a fantastic writer- and despite being only 33 years old and only very recently becoming famous, it seems as though she’s lived many lifetimes as she describes her time as a dominatrix/sex worker, a recovering drug addict, and her unlikely rise to fashion icon status, all with astute wisdom. With Down the Drain, Fox’s unique insights into womanhood (shaped by her experience growing up poor and unruly in New York City in the time of late-stage capitalism) comes to the light and reveals her to be so much more than a momentary meme or an air-headed caricature. This one is a must-read (especially for the girls and gays).“Sometimes you have to say fuck it and throw your life down the drain just to see where you’ll come out on the other side. The most profound beauty emerges from the ashes of destruction. And by that, I mean that sometimes you have to burn your life to the ground in order to experience the life that is truly meant for you. It is in letting go that we are forced to carve our own destiny. We must be willing to relinquish all we once held dear if we are holding on with fear. If you believe in the power within yourself, anything is possible. Because the truth is, anyone who is ‘someone’ first started out as a delusional dreamer.”...more
